Final Fantasy Tactics.

The three characters shown, from left to right, are Reis Du(e)lar (whether there's an e depends on the game version), Beowulf Cadmus / Kadmas (same), and Ramza Beoulve (the game's protagonist). Beowulf is a (former) Knight Templar and Reis' fiancé in a relationship mutually based in love.

The tl;dr of the story is that Reis is something known as a "Dragonkin": Her default form *resembles* that of a human, but the official description is "Human in appearance, but descended of dragons. The blood of the Holy Dragon flows in her veins." Due to FFT Engrish issues it's ambiguous as to whether this means she is human with a distant Dragon relative, or a sort of Dragonborn equivalent that's exceptionally human not unlike Yuan-Ti Purebloods.

Back to the tl;dr, Reis and Beowulf love each other. Very, very much. Unfortunately, there is another person, Celebrant Bremondt / Buremonda, who *also* 'loves' Reis. Reis, however, is infatuated with Beowulf (for good reason), and his attempts to pretty much literally buy her love all fail. Growing increasingly infuriated he strips Beowulf of his titles and brands him a heretic. Her love disgraced, Reis... remains with him even in exile, because IT'S LOVE.

Furious, Bremondt turns to dark arts in an attempt to strike Beowulf with a fatal curse. Reis throws herself in the way, and... well, see the results. Her Holy Dragon blood reacts spectacularly with the magic of the curse turning her into a literal fucking Dragon.

As part of an optional quest Ramza and Beowulf can eventually find a way to undo the curse and revert her back to her former (dubious nature) state. Key words *optional quest*. Furthermore if Ramza dismisses the pair before the quest's resolution, or Ramza doesn't accept a specific job in the first place, there's no chance for Reis to be turned back. And so: IT'S LOVE.
